Introduction¶

Project charter¶

Drive sales and brand awareness by using visitors interactions with the banks budgeting app to inform targeting, content generation, and app development to increase engagement, retention, and ultimately sales (loans, credit cards, checking/savings accounts).

Current Investigation¶

Hypothesis: There are distinct types of first time interactions that users have with the app that result in differentiated long-term user behavior (e.g. different expected lifetimes, higher rate of account enrollments).

Previously, we identified that the highest rates of churn tend to occur right after the first visit to the app. Therefore, understanding the first visit provides the opportunity for identifying factors that lead to churn and identifying potential solutions. By identifying patterns in what first visits to the app look like, the client will potentially be able to:

  • Assess which first visits result in the largest rate of churn to help inform app developers what should be addressed to retain potential churners most effectively during that first visit.
  • Get signals as to users' motivations for using the app, which could help to identify needs that are or are not met by the app.
  • Understand the types of visits that lead to higher rates of engagement, retention, and sales and assess the commonalities across the users who have these first visit types to shed light on what types of users are being well served by the app. This information could be used to inform targeting of marketing to bring in users more likely to get value from the app and therefore, remain engaged and potentially open an account.

Guiding Questions¶

  1. What do users first visits to the apps look like? (This is a proxy for intention in downloading the app).
  2. How do these visit types relate to:
    • Likelihood of returning to the app?
    • Lifetime of app usage?

Summary¶

Key decisions¶

  • The number of clusters was chosen as five in order to strike a balance between the silhouette score, inertia, and utility in a business setting.

Key Findings¶

  1. A segment of users come in and quickly explore all of the different app features and then leave. These users are the least likely t"o return - they saw everything and were not interested.
  2. Those who explore the app for an extended period of time during their first visit and make it back for a second visit show that they found value in the app and demonstrate longer lifetimes than all other segments.
  3. Those who set up a budget are most likely to return a second time.

Next steps¶

  • Assess demographic differences between clusters.
  • Dive deeper into the characteristics of users in the extended exploring cluster and assess whether specific pages or features lead to users return.

Each row represents a distinct visit to the app, and each column represents a feature of that visit. Visits are defined as groups of actions taken by an individual in a single session. Sessionization and entity resolution are determined by the backend instrumetation, and are assumed to be fixed for the purposes of this analysis.

Approach: Cluster first user visits based on behavior and content viewed¶

Scale the data¶

Before clustering, the data is scaled to give each feature equal weight in determining the distance between observations.

In [ ]:
scaled_features = feat_plot.scaled

Choosing k¶

K-means clustering requires choosing k, the number of clusters. To choose k, we can cluster using a range and comparing various performance metrics. Here, we will look at k between 2 and 8 and use the silhouette score and inertia to make our decision. We want to maximize the silhouette score and choose an inertia at the inflection point of the k-inertia graph.

In [ ]:
silhouette = []
inertia = []

for k in range(2, 9):    
    model = KMeans(n_clusters=k)
    model.fit(scaled_features)
    inertia.append(model.inertia_)
    silhouette.append(metrics.silhouette_score(scaled_features, model.labels_, metric='euclidean'))
In [ ]:
sv.plot(range(2,9), silhouette[1:], kind='scatter',
       xlabel='Number of clusters',
       ylabel='Silhouette score',
       title='Silhouette score versus number of clusters');
In [ ]:
sv.plot(range(2,9), inertia[1:], kind='scatter', 
        xlabel='Number of clusters',
        ylabel='Intertia',
        title='Inertia versus number of clusters');

From the above figures, the "elbow" of the inertia figure is approximately 5. The silhouette score is at the same value of k=5. This value of k is also beneficial as categorizations are typically most meaningful and interpretable when there are less than 7 categories to analyze within business contexts.

Assessing outcomes of the resulting clusters¶

The clusters can be described in terms of the features used to generate them as follows:

  • Cluster 1: Low number of pages, duration, time between pages, explores different pages
  • Cluster 2: Low number of pages, duration, time between pages, focus mainly on onboarding pages
  • Cluster 3: More pages, medium time between pages, explores different pages
  • Cluster 4: Longer duration, longer time between pages, focused on budgeting tool
  • Cluster 5: More pages, medium time between pages, mostly advice pages

The group that spends the most time on the app and sets up their budget is the most likely to return.

Conclusions¶

Key decisions¶

  • The number of clusters was chosen as five in order to strike a balance between the silhouette score, inertia, and utility in a business setting.

Key Findings¶

  1. A segment of users come in and quickly explore all of the different app features and then leave. These users are the least likely to return - they saw everything and were not interested.
  2. Those who explore the app for an extended period of time during their first visit and make it back for a second visit show that they found value in the app and demonstrate longer lifetimes than all other segments.
  3. Those who set up a budget are most likely to return a second time.

Next steps¶

  • Assess demographic differences between clusters.
  • Dive deeper into the characteristics of users in the extended exploring cluster and assess whether specific pages or features lead to users return.
